Package keystone.api.filters

Class KeystoneFilter

java.lang.Object
keystone.core.gui.widgets.inputs.fields.EditableObject
keystone.api.filters.KeystoneFilter
Direct Known Subclasses:
AnalyzeTool, DeleteEntitiesTool, FillTool, StructureFilter
public class KeystoneFilter extends EditableObject
A filter compilable by Keystone. All filters must contain a class which extends KeystoneFilter. Contains information relating to which FilterBoxes the filter is modifying, as well as several API functions

    • processBlock

      public void processBlock(int x, int y, int z, WorldRegion region)
      Ran for every block the filter is modifying after processRegion(WorldRegion). Use this for modifications that can be done on a per-block basis. Be sure that this code is self-contained, as this will be ran on multiple threads for improved performance, and as such is subject to race conditions
      Parameters:
      x - The x coordinate
      y - The y coordinate
      z - The z coordinate
      region - The WorldRegion that the block is in

    • processEntity

      public void processEntity(Entity entity, WorldRegion region)
      Ran for every entity the filter is modifying after processRegion(WorldRegion). Use this for modifications that can be done on a per-entity basis. Be sure that this code is self-contained, as this will be ran on multiple threads for improved performance, and as such is subject to race conditions
      Parameters:
      entity - The Entity that is being modified
      region - The WorldRegion that the entity is in

    • resolvePalettes

      public final BlockType[] resolvePalettes(BlockPalette... palettes)
      Calculate the entry of multiple BlockPalettes at the same random index. Use this matching related blocks, such as randomly selecting a log and leaf combo
      Parameters:
      palettes - A list of BlockPalettes
      Returns:
      An array containing the resolved Blocks, in the same order as the provided BlockPalettes

    • palette

      public final BlockPalette palette(String... contents)
      Create a BlockPalette from multiple block IDs. Any ID that is a valid ID for the /setblock command will work. Add a number after the ID to specify the block's weight in the palette, with a higher weight being more likely to be chosen. [e.g. "minecraft:stone_slab[type=top] 10"]
      Parameters:
      contents - A list of block IDs and optionally weights
      Returns:
      The BlockPalette that is generated
